[]: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Quote Post by Carl Horn &raquo; Wed Sep 27, 2006 10:56 pm The idea behind using accented English to portray Japanese that was originally accented is not necessarily to suggest the one &quot;correct&quot; equivalent &#40;it seems unlikely there could be such exact equivalency&#41; as to suggest the very important point that in real life these accents do exist, and people are constantly judged by them. Okayama people really do speak differently from people in Osaka, who in turn speak differently from people in Fukuoka, who in turn speak differently from those in Tokyo--supposedly, &quot;standard&quot; Japanese. I personally believe that a Brooklyn accent is more culturally similar to Kansai-ben than a &quot;Southern&quot; accent, but again the point is not so much to say which is correct, but to acknowledge that the character has a different background. It&#39;s supposed to be at least a little jarring--that&#39;s why it&#39;s considered an &quot;accent.&quot;

